      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monsey%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "After World War II, Monsey grew as a haven for Hasidic families seeking affordable land, leading to a boom of synagogues and yeshivas.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12,
        13,
        14
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Monsey%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "In 1944, Rabbi Shraga Feivel Mendlowitz founded Beth Medrash Elyon, Monsey’s first Jewish school, to train Torah teachers.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        19,
        20
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monsey%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "By 1997 Monsey boasted 112 synagogues and 45 yeshivas, reflecting its status as a major center of Orthodox Judaism.",
